Sample data (first dataset is used to force the bounds, second one is using the feature):

        var data = {
          labels: ['FWs', '3s', 'GIR', 'Ptts', 'PA'],
          datasets: [{
              fillColor: 'rgba(220,220,220,0)',
              strokeColor: 'rgba(220,220,220,0)',
              pointColor: 'rgba(220,220,220,0)',
              pointStrokeColor: '#fff',
              data: [0, 0, 0, 0, 100]
            }, {
              colorProgressive: true,
              colorMin: 'rgba(255, 0, 0, 0.5)',
              colorMax: 'rgba(0, 255, 0, 0.5)',
              pointStrokeColor: '#fff',
              data: []
            }
          ]
        };

Added mouseover colors as well as firing off JavaScript events on mouseover and mouseout for line points. Also changed the constructor so just the element is passed and not the context, otherwise you cannot attach the listener event.

This is something I did over the weekend.

I changed the constructor so that you have to pass the element rather than the context, and the code will automatically obtain the context from the element.

I had to do this otherwise I have no idea (code wise) what I need to bind the listener event to.

Now I knew doing this might go against the grain and won't be accepted, if it's not, then I will just simply make a spin off for myself and others to use, but I wanted to give it a shot to see if it would be accepted.

I also plan to implement this for Bars and other charts, just haven't gotten around to it yet.


Usage Example:
```json
			var data = {
				labels : ["January","February","March","April","May","June","July"],

				datasets : [
					{
						fillColor : "rgba(220,220,220,0.5)",
						strokeColor : "rgba(220,220,220,1)",
						pointColor : "rgba(220,220,220,1)",
						pointStrokeColor : "#fff",

						pointColorHover : "rgba(255,187,205,1)",
						pointStrokeColorHover : "rgba(255,187,205,1)",
						pointDotStrokeWidthHover : "rgba(255,187,205,1)",
						
						data : [65,59,90,81,56,55,40],

						mouseover: function(data) {
							console.log(data);
							console.log('over: look at me im in the data code!')
						},

						mouseout: function(data) {
							console.log(data);
							console.log('out: ook at me im in the data code!')
						}
					}
				]
			}
```

I implemented a basic title, which show (if defined) the title of the chart.

Title Defaults can be overwritten by adding a 3nd parameter to the "new Chart()" function, which represents the title and adding the showTitle : true to the options.

<pre><code>new Chart(ctx).Bar(data,options,title);</code></pre>

The following defaults can be overridden for the title:

<pre><code>Bar.defaults = {
	//Boolean - Whether to show the title
	showTitle : false,

	//String - Title label font declaration for the title label
	titleFontFamily : "'Arial'",

	//Number - Title label font size in pixels
	titleFontSize : 12,

	//String - Title label font weight style
	titleFontStyle : "normal",

	//String - Scale label font colour
	titleFontColor : "rgba(0, 0, 0, 1)"

}
</code></pre>

See here the example:

